1. hostname => Show or change a system’s hostname.

2. pwd => Print the current working directory’s path.

3. echo => Output text on the terminal.

4. ls => List the contents of a directory. -a, -l, -F, -R, -r, -i are some of the options that can be used with ls command.

5. cd => Change the current directory.

6. mkdir => Create a new directory.

7. cp => Copy files or directories.

8. mv => Move or rename files or directories.

9. rm => Delete files or directories.

10. touch => Create an empty file or update an existing file’s modification date.

11. cat => Read and output the contents of a file. '-n' flag will display line numbers.


*** bash is the most popular shell on Linux computers.


type
  Show how a specific command is executed.


env
  Display the current environment.
export
  Make local variables available to subprocesses.
unset
  Remove a variable.


tree
  Display a hierarchical listing of a directory tree


find
  Traverse a file system tree and search for files matching a specific set of criteria.
ls
  Show properties of files and directories and list a directory’s contents.
mkdir
  Create new directories.

rmdir
  Delete directories.
touch
  Create new empty files or update an existing file’s modification timestamp.
head 
  By default displays the first 10 lines of a file.
tail
  By default displays the last 10 lines of a file.
file
  Display the type of file, directory or etc. A quick way to identify the file type.
kill
  Use to terminate a process. The kill command allows you to send signals to processes based on their process ID (PID).
killall
  The killall command is a powerful way to stop processes by using their names rather than the PID numbers. You can use wildcards as well.
df
  Display how much disk space is available on an individual device. Use -h to get the output in human readable format (M for megabytes, etc)
du
  The du command shows the disk usage for a specifi c directory (by default, the current directory)
sort
  It sorts data in a file.
grep
  Use to search the content in a file. One of the widely used command.
